<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-287-946  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 287 946.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Information Week  March 26 1990 n263 p59(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>I want to run a software company. (Frank Dodge, president ofMcCormack and Dodge, files suit against Dun and Bradstreet Corp.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Soat, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>In response to Frank Dodge's $1.2 million lawsuit against Dun andamp;Bradstreet (D andamp; B), the company has issued a 150 page responsealleging that Dodge accepted a position at Dun andamp; BradstreetSoftware Services (DBS), then made impossible demands and refusedan offer that would enable him to resign and form his own softwarecompany.andP;  Dodge claims he did not see press releases concerningthe acquisition of DBS until the news was made public.andP;  He furtherstates that he was barred from McCormack and Dodge headquarters,the facilities of a company, also acquired by D andamp; B, that hefounded.andP;  The main issue in the lawsuit concerns the non-competeclause that allows Dodge to form his own software company only ifhe is fired, ensuring the safety of proprietary information.andO;Dodge claims that he was demoted and mistreated which constitutesde facto firing.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Company:   Dun and Bradstreet Corp. (cases)Dun and Bradstreet Software Services Inc. (cases).andO;Ticker:    DNB.andO;Topic:     Law SuitLegal IssuesPersonnel Problems.andO;Feature:   illustrationportrait.andO;Caption:   Frank Dodge. (portrait)Person:    Dodge, Frank (cases).andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>